title: For Sale/Trade:  Franklin Armory BFS Trigger
postcontent:
Note: The bases finish is purely cosmetic and does not affect balance or function of the trigger.This is a pull and release trigger from Franklin armory. I purchased this trigger to plink with my cmmg conversion bolt, hoewver due to the hammers size it will not hit home on the firing pin. It functions great with a standard bolt carrier, but for my purpose of one trigger for multiple bolt swaps it is just not there. Any standard bolt is fine, but the cmmg has a slightly smaller hammer gap. The reason for the thickness to these triggers for its safety disconnector. When one makes too rapid of shots it keeps the trigger from following the bolt. When this occurs just switch it back to semi and it will release the disconnector. By ATF ruling this is not a machine gun. The trigger is stated to have two seperate functions the "pull" and the "release." this trigger comes with everything that was sent; original packaging and all. The raised base is to be ground to meet perfectly to one's lower. If it sits too low, they come with peel away shims to raise it to meet any receiver tolerance. For myself I did as directed and gradually remove light layers until the trigger roll pins slid into place. The trigger has been tested for full functionality with sixty rounds and functioned as it was intended. The safety disconnector operated as it should without an issue. There are quite a few videos of this trigger in action. Certain setups will run better than others.
I will ship the trigger, but payment must be through PayPal $6 is needed for shipping.

title: For Sale:  Lefever DS 16 Gauge - TIGHT GUN, 80% CASE COLOR UNMOLESTED!
postcontent: General Specs: Lefever, Year 1913, 16 Gauge, 6lbs, SxS Serial Number: 66088 The Lefever DS or "Durston Special" is the entry level double from the Lefever Gun Co. of Syracuse, New York. It has the same internal action as there more expensive guns, but lacks cocking indicators and is unadorned in the way of engraving or other beauty treatments. Surprisingly, very few DS Grades were made in 16ga.. Bob Elliots book "UNCLE DAN LEFEVER MASTER GUN MAKER" estimates maybe 400 guns total production, so these are not often seen. This particular gun, sn66088 made in 1913, is one of the 400 and is in a pleasing "as found" condition. The entire gun is in FACTORY ORIGINAL CONDITION with no restorative work on any of the finishes. Weighing just 6lbs. it is an upland hunter's perfect little Lefever. There is a lot of original condition on the metal, with 80% factory case color, 90% blue on the barrels, 80% charcoal blue on the trigger guard, and most of the original finish remains on the wood.
